Better approach: every proper divisor d of n satisfies d ≤ n/2 (the largest). If d ≠ n/2 then d ≤ n/4 when 3∤n (because any d with n/4 < d < n/2 has 2 < n/d < 4, forcing n/d = 3, impossible). So d₂ ≤ n/4 and d₃ ≤ n/4.

f(n) ≤ n/2 + n/4 + n/4 = n. Strict: d₃ < d₂ so d₃ ≤ d₂ - 1 ≤ n/4 - 1. So f(n) ≤ n/2 + n/4 + (n/4 - 1) < n.

Actually in ℕ: n/2 + n/4 + n/4 ≤ n (can verify). And since d₂, d₃ are distinct, d₃ < d₂, so f(n) < n/2 + 2*(n/4) ≤ n. We just need d₂ + d₃ < n - n/2 = n/2 (roughly ⌈n/2⌉).

Let me use a simpler bound: d₁ ≤ n/2, d₂ ≤ n/2 - 1 (strictly less), d₃ ≤ n/2 - 2. No that's wrong, d₂ could be n/2 - 1 in principle.

Cleanest: every proper divisor d with d ≠ n/2 satisfies d ≤ n/4 (when 3∤n). So f(n) ≤ n/2 + 2*(n/4). And 2*(n/4) ≤ n/2 in ℕ. So f(n) ≤ n/2 + n/2 = n. But we need strict: since d₃ < d₂ ≤ n/4, d₃ ≤ d₂ - 1. And d₂ ≥ 1 (since 1 is a proper divisor). So f(n) ≤ n/2 + n/4 + (n/4 - 1) = n/2 + 2*(n/4) - 1 < n.
